==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Husky
<hw>Hus"ky</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Prob. for
<ets>husty</ets>; cf. OE. <ets>host</ets> cough, AS.
<ets>hw⟦omac⟧sta</ets>; akin to D. <ets>hoest</ets>, G.
<ets>husten</ets>, OHG. <ets>huosto</ets>, Icel. <ets>h⟦omac⟧sti</ets>.
See <er>Wheeze</er>.]</ety> <def>Rough in tone; harsh; hoarse; raucous;
<as>as, a <ex>husky</ex> voice</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Husky</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Husky
<hw>Hus"ky</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Powerful; strong;
burly.</def> <mark>[Colloq., U. S.]</mark></p>

<p><q>A good, <qex>husky</qex> man to pitch in the barnyard.</q>
<rj><qau>Hamlin Garland.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Husky</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Husky
<hw>Hus"ky</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu>pl. <plw>-kies</plw>
<pr>(#)</pr></plu>. <ety>[Cf. <er>Eskimo</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>An Eskimo.</def> <mark>[archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The Eskimo language.</def>
<mark>[archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>an Eskimo dog, especially a breed of strong
heavy-coated dogs used to pull dogsleds in the Northern regions of North
America.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

